---
import Shell from "../components/Shell.astro";
---

<Shell title="Triad | global and pairwise identity" description="A small identity broker with provider-global, account, and per-app identifiers.">
  <section class="hero shell">
    <p class="hero-signal">ONE HANDSHAKE. THREE EXPLICIT IDS.</p>
    <h1>IDENTITY,<br /><span>BOTH WAYS.</span></h1>
    <div class="hero-bottom">
      <p>
        Global when your apps need continuity. Pairwise when they need isolation.
        One small Triad broker for browser apps and devices without keyboards.
      </p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button primary" href="/demo/">TRY THE BROKER →</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="https://github.com/olstenlarck/triad-auth">VIEW SOURCE ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="identity-model shell" aria-labelledby="identity-title">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2 id="identity-title">ONE LOGIN.<br />NO IDENTITY GUESSING.</h2>
      <p>Email is profile data, not a key. Every token names exactly which identity contract it carries.</p>
    </div>
    <dl class="claim-ledger">
      <div>
        <dt>provider_sub</dt>
        <dd>prv_twitter_R4...</dd>
        <p>Provider-global and correlatable across Triad clients that receive it, without exposing the upstream ID.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <dt>account_sub</dt>
        <dd>acct_oD4s93...</dd>
        <p>Broker-global. Correlates one Triad account across clients.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="signal-row">
        <dt>pairwise_sub</dt>
        <dd>ps_9cqUe7...</dd>
        <p>Stable inside one app. Different client, different identifier.</p>
      </div>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="provider-band" aria-label="Supported identity providers">
    <div class="shell provider-list">
      <span>GOOGLE</span><span>GITHUB</span><span>TWITTER</span><span>CODE + PKCE</span><span>DEVICE FLOW</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="quickstart" class="quickstart shell" aria-labelledby="quickstart-title">
    <div class="section-heading compact">
      <h2 id="quickstart-title">POINT. REDIRECT. VERIFY.</h2>
      <p>Authorization Code + mandatory S256 PKCE. ES256 tokens. Standard JWKS.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="code-window" role="region" aria-label="Authorization request example" tabindex="0">
      <div class="code-meta"><span>GET /authorize</span><span>01 / 03</span></div>
      <pre><code>?client_id=triad-demo
&amp;provider=github
&amp;redirect_uri=http://localhost:8787/demo/callback/
&amp;code_challenge=...
&amp;code_challenge_method=S256</code></pre>
    </div>
    <ol class="flow-list">
      <li><strong>Broker upstream.</strong><span>Triad maps the provider's immutable identity, then discards the upstream access token.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Exchange once.</strong><span>Your app exchanges the short-lived code with its PKCE verifier.</span></li>
      <li><strong>Verify locally.</strong><span>Check ES256, issuer, audience, and expiry against the published JWKS.</span></li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="device-callout shell" aria-labelledby="device-title">
    <p class="device-code" aria-hidden="true">F7KQ-2M9X</p>
    <div>
      <h2 id="device-title">NO KEYBOARD?<br /><span>NO PROBLEM.</span></h2>
      <p>Issue a device code, let the user approve it in any browser, then poll the standard token endpoint.</p>
      <a class="text-link" href="/device/verify/">OPEN DEVICE VERIFICATION →</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Shell>
